Vietnam People's Daily-Gulf Cooperation Council Addresses Common Challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed Bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait.
It is worth noting that this is the first time Crown Prince Mohammed has visited Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to a diplomatic crisis in the Gulf.
During this crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a comprehensive embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations and having close relations with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal unity of the GCC and have had a negative impact on the economies of countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was only resolved at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, and the Gulf countries signed an agreement mediated by the United States and Kuwait to move towards “unity and stability”.
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are taking the lead in efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors in Qatar by the two countries.
The Gulf Arab countries' efforts to resolve their differences in order to restore relations with Qatar come from the requirement that they must unite for the benefit of all countries and regional stability, and aim to meet common challenges.
During the visit of the Saudi Crown Prince to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land passage between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer-long channel connecting the two countries will provide convenient conditions for citizens of the two countries to travel and integrate their supply chains.
The Saudi Arabian Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest US55 billion in Oman, and companies from the two countries have signed 13 memorandum of understanding on cooperation worth US330 billion.
The visit of the Saudi crown prince to the Gulf countries coincides with negotiations between Iran and the world's major powers to save the Iranian nuclear agreement called the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA)—an agreement condemned by Gulf Arab countries because they believe it cannot solve the missile problem with Iran.
The Gulf countries have always regarded Iran as a long-term “competitor” and regarded Iran's nuclear program as a “threat” to regional security.
The Gulf countries believe that it is flawed not to solve the Iranian missile problem and not to take action to curb Iran's activities in the region.
In the context of the failure of the nuclear negotiations between the major powers and Iran to meet the wishes of the Gulf countries, Saudi Arabia and Iran conducted direct negotiations.
